<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-08-12T15:24:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-08-12T15:24:00-05:00" n="779" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d779">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">760p.61/6: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Commissioner at Riga</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Young</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Riga</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-08-12T22:00:00+01:36"><hi rend="italic">August
                                            12, 1920—10 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received August
                                    13—9:40 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>107. Latvian-Bolshevik peace treaty follows closely similar treaties
                                with Esthonia and Lithuania. Russia advances 4,000,000 gold roubles,
                                agrees to return postal, telegraph, telephone, marine and railway
                                material, releases Latvia from responsibility Russian debts and
                                grants timber concessions. Both parties agree to conclude
                                commercial, transit and consular conventions. Mailing today
                                translation of the complete treaty.<note n="44" xml:id="d779fn44">Not printed.</note></p>
                            <p>Both countries planning to maintain for the present commercial
                                representatives only.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Young</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>